commodity narrative:
Retail demand remains busy for cheesemakers ahead of the autumn holidays. Inflation continues to affect individual customer purchasing ability, though, as private label cheeses have continued to garner more interest from retailers. Export movements from western and northern European countries into southern European countries have slowed, despite the holidays. Supplies are noted as mixed across the region, but generally balanced. Contractual talks for 2023 are ongoing, and prices are firming based on increasing logistical costs year over year.

commodity narrative:
Retail and food service demand for foreign style cheese is stable. However, consumers continue to look for discounts and store brands as a way to combat the effects of inflation. Cheese buyers are taking regular shipments and the occasional spot load to cover short term needs. But negotiations for extended business deals are tricky because of the price sensitivity within the market. Farm milk output is sufficient and supportive of active cheese production. Inventory levels of foreign-style cheese are mixed by variety. Some varieties are in good balance with market needs, while manufacturers of other varieties have to allocate supplies among customer orders, delaying some orders to help fill the most critical shipments first.

secondary source info:
EU YTD Cheese Production 
According to CLAL data made available to USDA, August EU cheese production, 796,323 MT is up 0.6 percent from August 2021. Total EU cheese production year to date through August 2022, is estimated at 6.338 million MT, a decrease of 0.8 percent from January - August 2021. Among some of the leading Western European cheese producing countries, the January - August 2022 cheese production and the percentage change compared with January - August 2021 are Germany, 1,644,471 MT, -1.9 percent; France, 1,133,270 MT, -0.2 percent; Italy, 795,550 MT, +0.4 percent; and Netherlands, 629,700 MT, -1.7 percent.

commodity narrative:
Demand for foreign type cheese is solid, but some industry sources note there may be bearish undertones appearing. Industry sources suggest cheese prices have eased back slightly in Europe and Oceania. Retail buyers are taking contracted amounts as expected, but additional demand is limited. Consumers are turning to lower cost items and store brands to ease the pain of inflation. Weak economic conditions in world markets are slowing some of the opportunity for exports. While cheese supplies are snug, they are, in many cases, just sufficient enough to cover any demand. Industry sources expect supplies to decrease through the Q4 holiday season, but without improved demand vigor, they think markets may track sideways.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS

methodology: Information for the period September 26 - 30, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Retail demand for European type cheeses is solid. Industry sources suggest that the requests have picked up speed since summer holidays have ended and Q4 holidays are drawing nearer. That said, consumers have become more price sensitive as well, looking for store brands and discounted cheese to fill their cheese needs. Food service demand and food manufacturing demand are mixed. Uncertainty with labor and energy availability, coupled with inflation, has subdued some buyer activity. Cheese production is active but also stymied by high energy costs, tight supplies of farm milk, and labor shortages. Inventories are shrinking as demand outpaces production. Some manufacturers are shorting shipments to stretch the available cheese supplies. Industry sources expect tight cheese stocks to be the norm through the Q4 holidays.

commodity narrative:
European cheese demand is firm within retail and food manufacturing settings. However, food service demand is mixed. Industry contacts suggest consumers are seeking out ways to stretch their food dollars. While this means foregoing some restaurant dining or specialty cheese items, shoppers are seeking out lower-cost alternatives, such as store brands, discounts, or smaller packaged items. Cheese orders are surpassing production and pulling inventories lower. A few manufacturers report not having the cheese supplies available to fill orders beyond their contracted volumes. European cheese output is subdued as milk production is seasonally declining, and there are lower component levels within the milk.

commodity narrative:
European cheese demand is firm within retail and food manufacturing settings. However, food service demand is mixed. Industry contacts suggest consumers are seeking out ways to stretch their food dollars. While this means foregoing some restaurant dining or specialty cheese items, shoppers are seeking out lower-cost alternatives, such as store brands, discounts, or smaller packaged items. Cheese orders are surpassing production and pulling inventories lower. A few manufacturers report not having the cheese supplies available to fill orders beyond their contracted volumes. European cheese output is subdued as milk production is seasonally declining, and there are lower component levels within the milk.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices decreased $.0325 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. Prices decreased $.1000 for wholesale Swiss cheese. All other prices are unchanged.
methodology: Information for the period September 5 - 9, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Industry contacts note that retail European cheese demand is trending higher as the summer holidays end. The growth is largely due to interest of shoppers seeking store brands and discounted goods. Specialty cheese items are finding sales but often in smaller package sizes as consumers seek to take the sting out of market prices. Food service demand is stable for many cheese varieties. Order fulfillment for commercial uses and exports is proving tricky as buyers are sensitive to increased costs, and sellers are hesitant to let too much of their inventories go. Foreign type cheese stocks are tight already, and with weak European farm milk intakes, it may be difficult for manufacturers to stay ahead of cheese orders if demand picks up significantly. Cheese production is on par with current milk supplies.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices decreased $.1000 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are unchanged.
methodology: Information for the period August 29 -  September 2, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Retail demand for European style cheese is growing as the summer holidays end. However, shoppers are becoming more interested in store brands and discounted varieties in lieu of specialty items. Many shoppers are trying to control their grocery bills and thwart the impacts of inflation. Food service cheese demand is stable but shifting from the prime tourism regions back to neighborhood restaurants. In some cases, restaurants and cheese outlets are facing some of the same labor issues that production facilities face, attracting enough workers and keeping them healthy. Cheese production is active, but only as much as tight milk supplies and worker availability allows. European cheese inventories are tight. Some industry contacts worry that cheese supplies may tighten further through the fall and winter months as milk volumes continue the seasonal decline and are kept low with limited feed availability and elevated milk production costs.

United States domestic cheese prices increased $.0500 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are unchanged.
methodology: Information for the period August 22 - 26, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
European cheese demand patterns are steady and consistent with what is typical for the end of summer. Industry sources describe retail demand as good, and food service orders are strong in the traditional tourist locations. However, in some cases, cheese shoppers are pushing back on the prices of cheese offered, especially in export markets. Oftentimes, manufacturers are not feeling a need to capitulate. Cheese production is steady to lower. Production schedules are as active as tight milk supplies and worker availability allow. Inventories are sufficient to cover most contracted orders, however, some varieties are tight, and cheese buyers are finding their orders getting pushed back in some cases.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices decreased $.0050 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are unchanged.
secondary source info:
EU cheese production January - June 2022, is estimated at 4.767 million MT, a decrease of 1.1 percent from January - June 2021 according to CLAL data made available to USDA. Among some of the leading Western European cheese producing countries, the January - June 2022 cheese production and the percentage change compared with January - June 2021 are Germany, 1,238,127 MT, -1.9 percent; France, 860,110 MT, unchanged; Italy, 600,840 MT, +0.9 percent; and Netherlands, 477,900 MT, -1.8 percent.

According to CLAL data made available to USDA, cheese exports from the EU27 January - June 2022, 675,000 MT, are down 0.8 percent from January - June 2021. Main destinations January - June 2022, quantity, and percent change from January - June 2021 are United Kingdom, 212,638 MT, +6.04 percent; United States, 63,290 MT, +2.36 percent; and Japan, 58,062 MT, -2.55 percent.

International cheese buyers are still price sensitive and reluctant to make additional buys. Domestic demand is healthy enough to keep inventories in check and is preventing manufacturers from building cushion stocks. As summer milk intakes seasonally decline, so does some cheese production volumes.

commodity narrative:
Demand patterns for European cheese have remained consistent with the previous weeks. While retail demand is in a summer lull, food service demand within major tourist destinations is stronger. Some industry sources suggest U.S sourced cheese is now at a price advantage over some varieties of European cheese. However, export sales are slow to develop. International cheese buyers are still price sensitive and reluctant to make additional buys. Domestic demand is healthy enough to keep inventories in check and is preventing manufacturers from building cushion stocks. As summer milk intakes seasonally decline, so does some cheese production volumes.

commodity narrative:
European cheese contacts relay that market conditions have not changed much given that many Europeans are still on their summer holidays. Contacts suggest demand for European cheese is stable. Cheese is moving through regular contracts, even as retail demand has slowed somewhat, and higher prices have made exporting cheese more challenging. Retail shoppers have transitioned to buying more store brands and discounted packages than regular brands or specialty items in response to inflation. Food service demand is mixed, being slightly lower in many areas, but higher in the prime tourist locations. Cheese inventories are keeping up with current demand, and production is steady to lower, tracking along seasonal declines in milk outputs. Manufacturers have been able to build a cushion of cheese stocks for some varieties, and the age profile in warehouses is better balanced.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices decreased $.0250 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are unchanged.
methodology: Information for the period August 1 - 5, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
European cheese demand has moderated as the summer holiday season has taken hold. Export orders are under some price pressures, and retail sales have decreased for some specialty items due to high inflation rates. That said, cheese sales are healthy enough to keep manufacturers and cheese purveyors content. Overall, supply and demand are in good balance. Cheese production is steady to lower, tracking with the seasonally lower milk intakes. With a calmer sales arena, aging facilities have been able to catch up on supplies. Industry contacts say the age profile within the warehouses has lengthened and is in better equilibrium across the cheese stocks. Contacts also think they need to build inventories, because, as holiday travelers return from their vacations, market participants think the pull on cheese supplies will increase, especially for retail cheese.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices decreased $.1275 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are unchanged.
methodology: Information for the period July 25 - 29, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative: European cheese stocks, although at low levels, are in generally good balance with demand. Industry sources suggest that overall cheese demand is up from the previous couple years. Orders from Southern Europe are strong due to summer holidays and tourism. Retail and food service orders are stable. Export opportunities are present, although exporters are facing competition and price reluctance from buyers. Cheese production is in line with the seasonal decline of milk intakes. However, drought conditions across much of Europe and elevated costs for energy and labor have created uncertainty for European cheese makers. If demand was to increase as Europeans return from summer holidays, and milk production continues to shrink, cheese manufacturers could face increased pressure on available cheese supplies.
secondary source info:
EU cheese production January - May 2022, is estimated at 3.96 million MT, a decrease of 1.4 percent from January - May 2021 according to CLAL data made available to USDA. Among some of the leading Western European cheese producing countries, the January - May 2022 cheese production and the percentage change compared with January - May 2021 are Germany, 1,031,003 MT, -2.0 percent; France, 720,920 MT, +0.3 percent; Italy, 499,390 MT -0.3 percent; and Netherlands, 395,900 MT, -3.3 percent. For Eastern EU27 countries, according to CLAL data made available to USDA, January - May 2022 cheese production in Poland was 391,360 MT, down 1.5 percent from January - May 2021.

According to CLAL data made available to USDA, cheese exports from the EU27 January - May 2022, 555,000 MT are up 0.2 percent from January - May 2021. Main destinations January - May 2022, quantity, and percent change from January - May 2021 are United Kingdom, 173,152 MT, +9.00 percent; United States, 51,625 MT, +5.91 percent; and Japan, 46,335 MT, -2.91 percent.
methodology: Information for the period July 18 - 22, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
European cheese supply and demand remain in good balance. Cheese inventories are available for most orders, and thanks to steady cheese production, those stock levels have stabilized and are at comfortable levels. While demand has slowed slightly, industry sources report that retail and food service orders are returning to pre-pandemic levels. Retailers suggest that shoppers, sensitive to higher prices at the checkout, are opting for smaller packaged cheeses or looking for bargain prices. Export interest is strong within the EU, but exporters are running into some price resistance outside the EU. Restauranteurs are seeing good demand, especially in the more active tourist regions.

commodity narrative:
European cheese supply and demand remain in good balance. Cheese inventories are available for most orders, and thanks to steady cheese production, those stock levels have stabilized and are at comfortable levels. While demand has slowed slightly, industry sources report that retail and food service orders are returning to pre-pandemic levels. Retailers suggest that shoppers, sensitive to higher prices at the checkout, are opting for smaller packaged cheeses or looking for bargain prices. Export interest is strong within the EU, but exporters are running into some price resistance outside the EU. Restauranteurs are seeing good demand, especially in the more active tourist regions.

Stronger food service demand is developing in the tourist destinations of Southern Europe, while lighter interest is present in other parts of the continent. Cheese production is active but limited by decreasing milk supplies.

commodity narrative:
Demand for foreign type cheese is still elevated. Orders from the retail sector are strong and have not subsided due to the increase in prices at the register. Ingredient cheese sales and orders from within the European Union are stable. While manufacturers are getting interest from export markets, logistical challenges hinder some growth in these sales opportunities. European cheese inventories are tight. Milk intakes that are declining seasonally have cheese makers competing for available milk. The tight milk supply and solid cheese demand are preventing manufacturers from building inventories to a more comfortable level. Instead, industry sources suggest cheese supply and demand are in balance.

As milk intakes decline seasonally, manufacturers are cautious to maintain the delicate balance between supply and demand for cheese.

Shoppers are seeking out store sales and other deals to ease the effects of higher prices at the checkout. Contacts say wholesale buyers are expecting travel, and the corresponding sales of cheese into restaurants and tourist destinations, to increase as well. However, export sales are not as easy. The high freight costs and cheese prices have dissuaded some international cheese buyers. European cheese stocks are still tight, but availability of some varieties is improving. As milk intakes decline seasonally, manufacturers are cautious to maintain the delicate balance between supply and demand for cheese.

commodity narrative:
Industry sources describe demand for foreign type cheese as good. Retail orders have remained healthy, and orders from other food processors are satisfactory. Contacts say export demand for European cheeses is mixed. While interest from within the European Union is stable, buyer interest outside the EU has run into some price resistance. The combination of the seasonal high-water mark for milk intakes, active cheese production, and a bit slower overall demand has allowed cheese inventories to grow in Europe. While stocks are still below typical levels, cheese is more available to fill orders as needed. Cheese demand appears to be in good balance with supply currently. However, cheese market participants are wary of how the supply and demand balance will progress. Milk output is starting to decrease along seasonal trends, and shifts in demand could put the market out of balance once again.

commodity narrative:
As the peak of the milk season passes, European style cheese makers are cautious in how they handle their inventories. The stock levels of cheese in aging facilities are still low, and the age profiles are young. With a little uncertainty on how plentiful milk intakes may be later in the summer, cheese makers are taking a wait and see approach to making offers. They are making as much cheese as the milk available allows and can fill most buyer requests, but they do not overextend offers beyond what they can produce. Likewise, buyers are not interested in buying more than immediate needs. Cheese demand has been healthy within both retail and food service sectors, however higher prices are meeting some buyer resistance.

Orders from the restaurant sector are growing ahead of the summer holiday season, but buyers and sellers are cautious, not wanting to overextend. Some industry contacts think this may not change for some time. European milk production is near its seasonal peak, and without more milk available for cheesemaking, it may be difficult to build any additional supplies.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices increased $.0800 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are unchanged.
secondary source info:
EU cheese production January - March 2022, is estimated at 2,302,189 MT, a decrease of 2.0 percent from January - March 2021 according to CLAL data made available to USDA. Among some of the leading Western European cheese producing countries, the January - March 2022 cheese production and the percentage change compared with January - March 2021 are Germany, 624,419 MT, +0.2 percent; France, 432,410 MT, +1.5 percent; Italy, 296,380 MT -1.1 percent; and Netherlands, 234,600 MT, -3.3 percent.

According to CLAL data made available to USDA, cheese exports from the EU27 January - March 2022, 326,000 MT are up 1.9 percent from January - March 2021. Main destinations January - March 2022, quantity, and percent change from January - March 2021 are United Kingdom, 96,986 MT, +14.28 percent; United States, 29,001 MT, +13.17 percent; and Japan, 26,481 MT, -6.06 percent.

Export sales are active, but contacts note a bit of resistance to the higher price offers. Manufacturers are not overly concerned with this reaction because there is still more demand than their supplies can meet. Stockpiles in aging facilities and warehouses are tight.

commodity narrative:
Demand for European cheese remains firm across all sectors. Orders are strong within retail channels, even as consumer prices at the check out increase. Restaurant sales are growing as temperatures warm, and cheese makers expect exports to be active this summer. However, inventories are low, and there is a young cheese profile in the aging facilities. Cheese production is active, but with tight milk intakes and challenges getting the labor needed, cheese production cannot fully keep pace with orders. Industry sources suggest reductions to deliveries are common.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices are unchanged for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, romano and other cheese varieties within this price series.
methodology: Information for the period May 2 - 6, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
While seasonal milk production is increasing, European cheese makers are still finding it difficult to stay ahead of market demand. Cheese production is active, but without more abundant milk supplies, or the labor to keep facilities running at full capacity, it is difficult to produce much more cheese. Industry sources relay that retail orders have eased somewhat following the spring holidays. But when coupled with a growing demand from restaurants and a steady pull from other food processors and export markets, the market demand is above what cheese makers can easily fill. Contracts are getting filled regularly, but many deliveries are cut or juggled to fill immediate needs first. Inventories are very tight, and aging facilities report a young age profile for cheese. Industry contacts expect the situation with tight supplies and healthy demand to continue for the near term.

Cheese production is active, but without more abundant milk supplies, or the labor to keep facilities running at full capacity, it is difficult to produce much more cheese. Industry sources relay that retail orders have eased somewhat following the spring holidays. But when coupled with a growing demand from restaurants and a steady pull from other food processors and export markets, the market demand is above what cheese makers can easily fill. Contracts are getting filled regularly, but many deliveries are cut or juggled to fill immediate needs first. Inventories are very tight, and aging facilities report a young age profile for cheese. Industry contacts expect the situation with tight supplies and healthy demand to continue for the near term.


FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices increased $.0350 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.
methodology: Information for the period April 25 - 29, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
European cheese supplies are tight, and without more farm milk output, it will be difficult for processors to expand cheese production. Industry sources say mozzarella, semi-hard and other cheese production facilities are competing for the available milk supplies. Cheese demand is strong in food service sectors as restaurant sales grow, thanks in part to improved weather creating a resurrection of outdoor dining. The strong food service demand, coupled with healthy food retail orders and stable export business, has supported cheese prices. Manufacturers continue to ask for higher prices. With lower cheese inventories to draw upon, buyers are willing to take what they currently need, but are more hesitant to make longer term arrangements. In some cases, manufacturers have to allocate cheese among the contracted buyers, shorting some loads so that the most pressing needs are filled, and no one goes without some cheese.

FOREIGN TYPE CHEESE WHOLESALE PRICE ADJUSTMENTS
United States domestic cheese prices increased $.0425 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.
methodology: Information for the period April 18 - 22, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Prices for European cheese continue to rise. Industry contacts report that cheese production is as active as the available milk allows. However, European milk production is sluggish, and cheesemakers must compete for milk supplies with other dairy processors. As a result, they are unable to keep up with demand, and cheese inventories remain low. Within aging facilities, the age of the cheese stored there tends to be younger than typical. Retail outlet demand is strong ahead of the spring holidays, and restaurant sales are higher, but industry analysts are questioning how consumers will react to rising prices. Market observers note more shoppers are seeking out private labels and specials to gain some relief from higher prices.

Some cheese manufacturers are finding it more difficult to meet consumers' predilection for cheese. Wholesale cheese prices are rising, and some contacts note that the cost increases are getting passed on to consumers. Some believe it will take some time to sort out how shoppers will respond to the higher cheese prices found at the checkout line.

Some cheese manufacturers are finding it more difficult to meet consumers' predilection for cheese. Wholesale cheese prices are rising, and some contacts note that the cost increases are getting passed on to consumers. Some believe it will take some time to sort out how shoppers will respond to the higher cheese prices found at the checkout line.

commodity narrative:
Cheese production in Germany continues to juggle very high demand that is expected to increase further, against lower estimated current YOY production below factory capacity. Sluggish seasonal milk progression is restraining cheese output. The dual challenges of driver shortages and higher transportation costs hover over cheese markets. Western European cheese prices are increasing. Sources report that cheese manufacturers are asking significantly higher prices.

United States domestic cheese prices increased $.1075 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.
secondary source info: Western European cheese production during January 2022, decreased 1.8 percent from January 2021 according to CLAL data made available to USDA.
methodology: Information for the period March 28 -  April 1, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Germany produces more cheese than any other country in Western Europe. While Germany and other top cheese producers struggled to keep pace with demand through much of 2021, early indications for 2022 show Germany producing more cheese than in 2021. Data for most other Western European countries is not yet released.

Primarily regular cheese customers stand at the front of the line to sign contracts with manufacturers in Western Europe. Supplies remain tight because all segments of internal EU and export customers are pressing for supply commitments. Some already booked orders are being cut due to insufficient cheese availability. There continues to be a shortage of trucks that can be scheduled to move  cheese to commercial customers. Pricing is firm and some manufacturers are trying to enforce price increases.

United States domestic cheese prices decreased $.0950 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.
secondary source info: Official January 2022 dairy production data for Western European countries is rolling out country by country. Germany reports January 2022 cheese production increased 2.7 percent according to CLAL data made available to USDA. Cheese production in Italy for January decreased 1.6 percent from January 2021.
methodology: Information for the period March 21 - 25, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
The Western European cheese market remains steady, with continuous demand and very tight stocks. Reports about this market have changed little in recent months because market conditions have not changed appreciably. Official Western European January 2022 cheese production data has been slow to appear. As the first to report Western European cheese production for the first month of 2022, Italy had reduced January 2022 cheese production. Throughout the primary Western European cheese producing areas, persistent tight supplies are widely expected to continue into coming months, keeping prices near or above current levels.

United States domestic cheese prices increased $.1425 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.
secondary source info: Italy, among the top cheese producers, has now reported that Italian January 2022 cheese production declined 1.6 percent from January 2021 according to CLAL data made available to USDA.
methodology: Information for the period March 14 - 18, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
Western European cheese manufacturers report that it has become increasingly difficult to obtain cheese additives and packaging materials. This compounds the factor of less milk than plants can handle thus, keeping cheese stocks tight. Adding in significant delivery bottlenecks, cheese from Western Europe remains far less available than factory capacity could provide absent these obstacles. 

This tightness is expected to continue for coming months. Costs are becoming more unpredictable. The large numbers of refugees from Ukraine remain an unknown in terms of demand for cheese to feed them. All the uncertainty is now causing higher price demands to be enforced in new contract negotiations. Some manufacturers are also enforcing surcharges. Higher prices are ahead.

United States domestic Swiss cheese prices increased $.0375, $.0800 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.

commodity narrative:
The EU exports more cheese to the United States than anywhere except the United Kingdom. This reflects longstanding trade patterns established until recently when the UK left the EU. During 2021, EU cheese production increased. Exports decreased. This outcome is consistent with the prevalence of very tight cheese stocks in the EU spanning quite some time. Stocks are very tight and domestic demand competes with export demand. No relief is expected anytime soon.

United States domestic cheese prices increased $.0125 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.
secondary source info:
Western European cheese production January  December 2021, 9,487,000 MT, increased 1.1 percent from January  December 2020 according to CLAL data made available to USDA. The percentage of 2021 EU cheese production from some top countries is: Germany, 26 percent; France, 18 percent; Italy, 13 percent; and Netherlands and Poland, each 10 percent. For the top cheese producing countries, 2021 YOY production varied as follows: Germany, +0.5 percent; France, +2.5 percent; Italy, -1.3 percent; Netherlands, -3.0 percent; and Poland, +3.6 percent.

Western European exports of cheese January  December 2021, 1,386,000 MT, decreased 1.2 percent from January  December 2020 according to CLAL data made available to USDA. Top export destinations, volumes and percent change for the period are: United Kingdom, 424,908 MT, -13.83 percent; United States, 132,930 MT, +12.89 percent; and Japan, 118,334 MT, -7.59 percent.
methodology: Information for the period February 28 -  March 4, 2022, issued weekly

commodity narrative:
The situation for foreign cheese continues in the same trajectory as recent months.  In the primary Western European cheese producing countries, demand is consistently good. Supplies remain tight. Internal EU demand typically firms in spring and the same result is expected this year. With low stocks, that will keep pressure on pricing. 

During 2021 cheese production increased in Western Europe while exports decreased. This is due to increased cheese consumption in the EU. Cheese importers are kept scrambling to source cheese from Western Europe. Manufacturers note however, that the historically largest importers from Western Europe often get priority in sales over the occasional or more marginal importing countries. The United States remains a top export destination, which tends to give U.S. buyers an edge over many other buyers in securing cheese from Western Europe.

United States domestic cheese prices increased $.0700 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.

Top export destinations, volumes, and percent change are: United Kingdom, 424,908 MT, -13.83 percent; United States, 132,930 MT, +12.89 percent; and Japan, 118,334 MT, -7.59 percent.
methodology: Information for the period February 21 - 25, 2022, issued weekly

Western European countries are the top sources for cheese imported into the United States. Market conditions in Western Europe are fundamentally unchanged. Allocation of some contracted orders continues due to tight supplies. All of these factors will merge to maintain price pressure in coming months. Forward contracting is proceeding at higher pricing.

commodity narrative:
Continuing price strength for cheese manufactured in Western Europe is no surprise. There was a slight increase in aging stocks primarily because manufacturers want to eke out an increase. Aged cheese has been sacrificed to meet demand for cheese with little age. There is going to be a renewed effort to rebuild aging stocks while addressing short term demand. 

New or infrequent buyers will be most affected in being passed over. Buying interest is strong from within the EU as well as from export customers. Many buyers are more focused on getting cheese than on price. Western European pricing, even with recently higher logistics costs, is not deterring buying interest. Most current production is going to existing customers. That will remain the priority. Contracting is well underway into Q2 2022.

commodity narrative:
United States consumers are buying ever more foreign cheese, especially from Europe. The top source of U.S. cheese imports, Italy, supplies nearly twice as much cheese as the second highest source, France. 

Foreign cheese imports to the United States continue to struggle against constrained production related to tight milk supplies. European cheese manufacturers increasingly comment on worker shortages as COVID leads to people staying home. Transport slowdowns have increased and sustain. Cheese production and transport remain top dairy priorities in Europe. But the current dynamics are expected to be with us for coming weeks.

Foreign cheese imports to the United States continue to struggle against constrained production related to tight milk supplies. commodity narrative:
Cheese supplies in the primary Western European cheese producing countries continue to be tight. The theme of recent months continues into 2022. While cheese production has edged higher over the arc of 2021, demand has also increased. COVID has also impacted production and distribution. Absences in manufacturing and transportation jobs are having an impact. The numbers of workers staying home has slowed the ability to transport products to stores, ports, and commercial customers. This is aggravating the impact of already tight cheese stocks. 

United States domestic cheese prices increased $.0825 for blue, gorgonzola, parmesan and romano. All other prices are steady.
secondary source info:
Western European cheese production January  October 2021 increased 1.9 percent from January  October 2020 according to data supplied by the European Commission.  Western European exports of cheese January  October 2021 increased 0.3 percent from January  October 2020 according to CLAL data made available to USDA. The largest export volumes go to the United Kingdom, followed by the United States, then Japan.

United Kingdom cheese production January  October 2021 was steady with January  October 2020 according to CLAL data supplied to USDA. United Kingdom exports of cheese January  October 2021 decreased 20.2 percent from January  October 2020 according to CLAL data made available to USDA. The largest export volumes go to Ireland, followed by Belgium, then France.
methodology: Information for the period January 3 - 7, 2022, issued weekly
